w:r.w:t: Hi everyone,
I've found out why the optimizer is estimating 1 for these rows in the execution plan.
Recall that the 2 lines in question in the plan do a 'PARTITION LIST SINGLE' on local primary key
index.
The column in question in each case, is WORKFLOW_ID, and the value is the same for each row
of the entire partion.Â ie, in partition WORKFLOW10839, the value is 10389 for every row.
And there are 5.6M rows for the WORKFLOW10839 partition (in TRADEBALANCE_MARKTOMARKET), and
over Â 3M for for WORKFLOW10839 (in Â INSTRUMENT).
The stats had been collected for partition WORKFLOW10839 Â 10 days ago, and they confirmed that
the number of rows was 5.6M and 3M.
So, why then was the optimizer estimating 1 row per partition, when it knew quite well that there
were many more than that?
I talked to Martin about this, and he suggested looking at the histograms.Â Turned out he was right
that histograms were the cause, but not for the reasons we originally thought.

no

The optimizer sees the cardinality is 5346335 (our original 5.3M), but then concludes that the
computed cardinality is 1.Â Â Why?
The clue is in the min and max values outlined in blue.Â 9345 again.
So, although there is no histogram on that column, the optimizer has still consulted the histogram values
to determine the min and max values in the partition.Â And, as we are seeking 10839, it concludes
that there will 0 rows matching 10839, which is then rounded to 1.
Well, that explains the 1.Â But why would it do that?Â Is it a bug?
Well, it seems that it isn't a bug.Â

high and low values in there.
